article.description: Tan White scored 25 points and Tamika Whitmore added 22 as the Fever beat the Liberty 91-70 to remain the WNBA's only unbeaten team.
article.headline: White, Whitmore help Fever remain undefeated
article.linkText: White, Whitmore help Fever remain undefeated
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Any questions the Indiana Fever had about their offense were answered for at least one night.

Tan White scored 25 points and Tamika Whitmore added 22 as the Fever beat the New York Liberty 91-70 on Tuesday night to remain the WNBA's only unbeaten team.

Anna DeForge added 14 points as the Fever improved to 4-0 for the first time in franchise history.

The Fever won their first three games behind the league's stingiest defense -- while averaging just 68 points. Against New York, they scored 16 more than their previous season high and fell three points short of a franchise record. It was the most points the Fever have scored in a non-overtime game.

It was an impressive performance for a team that has just four holdovers from last year's Eastern Conference finalists.

"I guess when you get a new group together, you worry about how they'll fit together," Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "I thought we'd fit together defense- and rebounding-wise. I thought the offense would take a while to catch up. But we had a good game offensively."

Becky Hammon had 20 points for New York (0-3), which remained one of the league's three winless teams.

Indiana put up its big offensive numbers with limited minutes from its top scorer. Tamika Catchings played 20 minutes because of a strained right foot and scored seven points. She was glad to see the Fever play well with her on the bench so much.

"We were able to spread the offense out ... it was an all-around effort," she said.

New York has allowed at least 91 points in each of its three games while losing by a combined 73 points -- with none closer than 17.

"I think we're just playing with a lack of emotion," Hammon said. "I think you could see in the second half, we played with a little more fire. We have got to learn to come out of the gates like that and be more disciplined."

DeForge hit three 3-pointers in the first quarter to help the Fever take a 19-16 lead at the end of the period.

Shameka Christon, the Liberty's top scorer through the first two games, twisted her left ankle with 5:50 left in the first quarter but returned to start the second quarter. She finished with 12 points.

The Fever took control with a 32-point second quarter. Whitmore scored 13 of her 19 first-half points in the period to give the Fever a 51-34 halftime lead.

Indiana shot 6-for-10 from the 3-point line in the first half, led by DeForge's 4-for-4 effort. The Fever held New York to 37 percent shooting before the break.

New York cut Indiana's lead to 60-51 on a Hammon basket with 3:46 left in the third quarter, but the Fever responded with an 8-0 run and took a 72-56 lead into the fourth quarter.

Former Fever center Kelly Schumacher, traded to New York in the offseason, had 13 points and seven rebounds in her return to Indiana.

"I think we are a young team that only seems to play well in spurts," Schumacher said. "We have all the talent in the world in this locker room. We need to quit making silly mistakes. I think that cost us the game tonight."
